Introduction and Objective

My study explores discover the effect of high-frequency noise on an image and applies Gaussian Blur to remove those noises. High-frequency noise affects fine details and edges, making the image appear distorted. I analyze how this noise changes the images intensity and variance and test whether Gaussian Blur can effectively remove it.

My objective is to examine how high-frequency noise impacts image quality and to assess the effectiveness of Gaussian Blur in reducing those noises. In addition, I aim to identify its limitations, especially in preserving edges, and explore advanced filtering techniques for future improvements.

Implementation with Justification

My process starts with generating random noise to an image up to 150. To generate high-frequency noise, I use the noise image to subtract and apply Gaussian Blur (Low-pass filter). I choose the bird image for this experimentation. After I have the bird image with high-frequency noise, I extract those high-frequency noises by applying a Low-pass filter into it to remove those noises.

In[4]:
import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load and convert image
image = cv2.imread('bird.jpg')
image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# Generate noise
noise = np.random.randint(0, 150, image.shape, dtype='uint8')

# Apply Gaussian blur (Low-pass filter)
low_pass_filter = cv2.GaussianBlur(noise, (5, 5), sigmaX=1.0)

# Extract high-frequency noise (Subtract low-frequency components)
high_frequency_noise = cv2.subtract(noise, low_pass_filter)

# Add noise to the image
image_noise = image + noise
image_high_frequency_noise = np.clip(image + high_frequency_noise, 0, 255).astype('uint8')

# Apply Gaussian blur for denoising
denoised_image = cv2.GaussianBlur(image_high_frequency_noise, (13,13), sigmaX=9)

# Plot everything in 2 rows, 3 columns
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

# Row 1
plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)
plt.title("Original Image")
plt.imshow(image)

plt.subplot(2, 3, 2)
plt.title("Noisy Image (Full Spectrum)")
plt.imshow(noise)

plt.subplot(2, 3, 3)
plt.title("Extract High-Frequency Noise")
plt.imshow(high_frequency_noise)


plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)
plt.title("Image with Full Spectrum Noise")
plt.imshow(image_noise)

plt.subplot(2, 3, 5)
plt.title("Image with High-Frequency Noise")
plt.imshow(image_high_frequency_noise)

plt.subplot(2, 3, 6)
plt.title("Denoised Image (Gaussian Blur)")
plt.imshow(denoised_image)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Discussion and Analyses

The background looks clearer in the high-frequency noise image because the noise enhances fine details, making smooth areas (like the background) more defined. The feathers look few purple because the noise affects color channels differently, exaggerating small color variations that werent noticeable before.

To compare the orginal image with image with high-frequency noise and denoised image, I compare them by mean and variance of its image.

In[2]:
# Function to compute mean and variance of an image
def compute_metrics(image):
    mean = np.mean(image)
    variance = np.var(image)
    return mean, variance

# Compute metrics for each image
mean_original, var_original = compute_metrics(image)
mean_high_freq, var_high_freq = compute_metrics(image_high_frequency_noise)
mean_denoised, var_denoised = compute_metrics(denoised_image)

# Print results
print("Image Metrics Comparison:")
print(f"Original Image   - Mean: {mean_original:.2f}, Variance: {var_original:.2f}")
print(f"High-Freq Noise  - Mean: {mean_high_freq:.2f}, Variance: {var_high_freq:.2f}")
print(f"Denoised Image   - Mean: {mean_denoised:.2f}, Variance: {var_denoised:.2f}")

Image Metrics Comparison:
Original Image   - Mean: 85.82, Variance: 2309.35
High-Freq Noise  - Mean: 98.93, Variance: 2485.73
Denoised Image   - Mean: 98.93, Variance: 1497.85

From the result, I found that high-frequency noise has a higher mean than the original image, meaning the noise values increase pixel intensity across regions. In addition to this, the high-frequency noise image (2485.73 variance) had a higher variance than the original (2309.25), meaning the high-frequency noise image increases brightness and noise.

However, the variance of the denoise image significant drops as Gaussian Blur smoothed out the noise, and the mean between high-frequency noise and denoised image is the same, proving that the denoise image won't change the brightness.

Conclusion

From my findings, it can be seen that Gaussian Blur completely removes high-frequency noise from the image with a higher kernel size and sigma value. However, the image becomes blurry and does not preserve the edges. The majority of high-frequency noise appears in the background, and if we use Gaussian Blur in this case, it will blur the entire image.

My future work might explore more advanced filtering techniques (bilateral filtering or non-local means denoising) to reduce noise while preserving fine details.
